"\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<      \[Rho][x] = \>", \[Rho][
          x]];\)\ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<      \[Rho][0] = \>", \[Rho][0]];\)\ \)}], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
We can conjecture that the limit of the collocation polynomial is the circle \
of curvature. \
\>", "Text"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["Derivation of the Radius of Curvature",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]]], "Text",
  TextAlignment->Left],

Cell[TextData[{
  "\tThe standard derivation of the formula for radius curvature involves the \
rate of change of the unit tangent vector.  This new derivation starts with \
the collocation the collocation circle to go through the three points  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{\(x - h\), 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x - h)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  ",  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"x", 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  ",  and  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{\(x + h\), 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x + h)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  "  on the curve  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(y = f \((x)\)\)]],
  ".  The limit as ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(h \[Rule] 0\)]],
  " is the osculating circle to the curve  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(y = f \((x)\)\)]],
  " at the point ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"x", 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  ".  The radius of curvature and formulas for the location of its center are \
simultaneously derived.  The computer algebra software ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " is used to assist in finding the limits.   "
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "\tStart with the equation ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(\((x - a)\)\^2 + \((y - b)\)\^2 = r\^2\)]],
  ",  of a circle.  Then write down three equations that force the \
collocation circle to go through the three points  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{\(x - h\), 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x - h)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  ",  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{"x", 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  ",  and  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"(", 
        RowBox[{\(x + h\), 
          StyleBox[",",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], \(f \((x + h)\)\)}], ")"}]]],
  "  on the curve  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(y = f \((x)\)\)]],
  ".  Enter the equations into ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " "
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(Clear[a, b, f, h, r, x];\)\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(eqn1\  = \ \ \((x - h - a)\)\^2 + \((f[x - h] - b)\)\^2 \[Equal] 
        r\^\(\(2\)\(\ \ \)\)\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(eqn2\  = \ \ \ \ \ \ \((x - a)\)\^2\ \  + \ \ \ \ \((f[x] - b)\)\^2\ \ \
\  \[Equal] r\^\(\(2\)\(\ \ \)\)\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(eqn3\  = \ \ \(\(\((x + h - a)\)\^2 + \((f[x + h] - b)\)\^2\)\(\[Equal]\
\)\(r\^2\)\(\ \ \)\)\)}], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "Solve the equations for ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"a", 
        StyleBox[",",
          FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], 
        RowBox[{"b", " ", 
          StyleBox["and",
            FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], " ", "r"}]}]]],
  " and extract the formula for the radius of the collocation circle.  Since \
it depends on ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      RowBox[{"x", " ", 
        StyleBox["and",
          FontFamily->"Times New Roman"], " ", "r"}]]],
  " we will store it as the function ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(r[x, h]\)]],
  ".    "
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(eqns = {eqn1, eqn2, eqn3};\)\ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(solset = Solve[eqns, {a, b, r}];\)\ \ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(r[x_, h_] = 
        PowerExpand[
          MapAll[FullSimplify, 
            solset\_\(\(\[LeftDoubleBracket]\)\(2, 1, 2\)\(\
\[RightDoubleBracket]\)\)]\ ];\)\ \ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<Solve the equations\>"];\)\ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print[TableForm[eqns]];\)\ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<Get\>"];\)\ \ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<r[x,h] = \>", r[x, h]\ ];\)\ \ \)}], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "The formula looks bewildering and one may wonder if it is of any value.  \n\
However, we can demonstrate the power of ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " and see if it can take the limit.  "
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(r[x_] = 
        Limit[r[x, h], h \[Rule] 0, 
          Analytic \[Rule] True];\)\ \ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<r[x] = \>", \*"\"\<\!\(lim\+\(h \[Rule] 0\)\)\>\"", "\< \
r[x,h]\>"];\)\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<r[x] = \>", \*"\"\<\!\(lim\+\(h \[Rule] 0\)\)\>\"", "\< \>", 
        r[x, h]];\)\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print["\<r[x] = \>", \ r[x]\ ];\)\ \ \)}], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "The computer gets the correct formula, but leaves out all the human \
understanding.  The formula for  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(r[x, h]\)]],
  " can be rewritten so that human insight and inspiration is involved, but \
the computer cannot think of the formulas we desire to see.  So human \
intervention must be called upon and the simplifications must be typed in by \
hand.   "
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(r[x, 
          h] \[Equal] \ \(\@\(h\^2 + \((F[x] - F[x - h])\)\^2\)\ \@\(h\^2 + \
\((F[x + h] - F[x])\)\^2\)\ \@\(4\ h\^2 + \((F[x + h] - F[x - \
h])\)\^2\)\)\/\(2\ h\ \((F[x + h] - 2\ F[x] + F[x - h])\)\);\)\)], "Input"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(r[x, 
          h]\  \[Equal] \(\@\(\(h\^2\) \((1 + \((F[x] - F[x - h])\)\^2\/h\^2)\
\)\)\ \@\(\(h\^2\) \((1 + \((F[h + x] - F[x])\)\^2\/h\^2)\)\)\ \@\(4\ \
\(h\^2\) \((1 + \((F[x + h] - F[x - h])\)\^2\/\((2  h)\)\^2)\)\)\)\/\(2\ h\^3\
\ \((\(F[x + h] - 2\ F[x] + F[x - h]\)\/h\^2)\)\)\ \ ;\)\)], "Input"],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(\(r[x, 
          h]\  \[Equal] \(\@\(1 + \((\(F[x] - F[x - h]\)\/h)\)\^2\)\ \@\(1 + \
\((\(F[h + x] - F[x]\)\/h)\)\^2\)\ \@\(1 + \((\(F[x + h] - F[x - h]\)\/\(2  h\
\))\)\^2\)\)\/\(\(\ \)\(\(F[x + h] - 2\ F[x] + F[x - h]\)\/h\^2\)\)\ \ \
;\)\)], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "Notice that when we take the limit as ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(h \[Rule] 0\)]],
  ", the limiting value for each of the radicals in the numerator is  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(\@\(1 + \(F'\)[x]\^2\)\)]],
  ".  ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " is capable of finding them, we illustrate this with the third one."
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(lim1 = 
        Limit[\@\(1 + \((\(F[x + h] - F[x - h]\)\/\(2  h\))\)\^2\)\ , 
          h \[Rule] 0, 
          Analytic \[Rule] True];\)\ \ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print[\*"\"\<\!\(lim\+\(h \[Rule] 0\)\)\>\"", "\< \>", \
\*"\"\<\!\(\@\(1 + \((\(F[x + h] - F[x - h]\)\/\(2  h\))\)\^2\)\) = \>\"", 
        lim1\ ];\)\)}], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "Therefore, the limit in the numerator is ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(\((1 + \(F'\)[x]\^2)\)\^\(3/2\)\)]],
  ".  The difference quotient in the denominator is recognized as the \
numerical approximation formula for the second derivative, hence the is  ",
  Cell[BoxData[
      \(\(F''\)[x]\)]],
  ".  "
}], "Text"],

Cell[BoxData[{
    \(\(lim2 = 
        Limit[\ \(F[x + h] - 2\ F[x] + F[x - h]\)\/h\^2\ , h \[Rule] 0, 
          Analytic \[Rule] True];\)\ \ \), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    \(\(Print[\*"\"\<\!\(lim\+\(h \[Rule] 0\)\)\>\"", "\< \>", \
\*"\"\<\!\(\(F[x + h] - 2\\\ F[x] + F[x - h]\)\/h\^2\) = \>\"", 
        lim2\ ];\)\)}], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
  "We already knew that ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " knows the rules for taking limits of functions when the formula is given. \
 Now we know that it has the \"artificial intelligence\" to rearrange \
quantities involving an arbitrary function and can identify difference \
quotients for approximating derivatives and find their appropriate limits.  \
It takes quite a bit of trust to let ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " do our thinking.  From the steps we filled in, we can gain trust for the \
computer's way of doing it.  "
}], "Text"],

